Installation of MM_SuperCC
--------------------------

 1. Copy 'MM_SuperCC.rexx' to 'MM:Rexx/'.
 2. Copy 'MM_SuperCC.cfg' to 'MM:Config/'.
 3. Copy 'MM_SuperCC.guide' to 'MM:Docs/'.
 4. Create a new directory (suggestion: 'MM:Config/MM_SuperCC/') where you
    store your mailing-lists.
 5. Edit the @{"config-file" link "Configuration" 0} according to your system-setup.

 NOTE: for the german version copy the according "_GER"-files instead !

 If you want to use MM_SuperCC.rexx from within @{"MailManager" link "MailManager" 0}s menu-bar, enter
 a new line in 'MM:Config/MailManager.cfg' looking like

 #AREASMENU "Super CC" "rx MM:Rexx/MM_SuperCC.rexx" "S"

 where "Super CC" is the name of the entry in the menu and "S" is the hot
 key used to start the program (together with right-Amiga).

 As an alternative to this you can configure MM_SuperCC.rexx as show above
 in MM_Prefs (User/Areas Menu).
@endnode
@prev "Distribution"
@node "Configuration" "MM_SuperCC.guide/Configuration"
@next "Usage"
Configuration of MM_SuperCC
---------------------------

 The config-file is made up of 12 keywords.

 #NODELISTPATH <directory>

    This is the directory where you store your nodelists.

    Example: #NODELISTPATH Nodelist:

 #MAILINGLISTS <directory>

    This is the directory used for storing your mailing-lists. You
    have to create it first during @{"installation" link "Installation" 0}.

    Example: #MAILINGLISTS MM:Config/MM_SuperCC/

    Mailinglist just hold addresses/tags to where the text shall be sent,
    one per line. The format of one line is:

    <4D-address>[@<domain>] [<name>]

    for adresses in FTN.

    If <domain> is omitted, MM_SuperCC will use default-domain.
    If <name> is omitted, MM_SuperCC will try to get the name from the node-
    list. If it can't be found, 'Unknown' will be used as the name.

    The format for InterNet-addresses is

    *<FQDA> [<realname>]

    For echotags use

    #<tagname> [<to-name>]

 #CONVERT <nodelist> <domain>

    This keyword is used for the nodelist->domain conversion. The first
    thing to do after starting MM_SuperCC.rexx is to select the nodelist
    which will be used. If the name of the nodelist is <nodelist> the program
    will use <domain> as domain. If the name of the nodelist is not mentioned
    in the config-file, the nodelist-name will also be used as the domain.
    '#CONVERT' may occure more than only once.

    Example: #CONVERT nodelist fidonet

    Which will mean: each time you select a nodelist with the name 'nodelist.*'
    MM_SuperCC.rexx will use 'fidonet' as domain. Otherwise it would use
    'nodelist' as domain (which is senseless).

 #TEXTDIR <directory>

    This is the directory where you usually store your textfiles. When asking
    for the file to be sent, MM_SuperCC will pop up a filerequester with this
    as the default-path.

 #EDITOR <command>

    This is the COMPLETE (!) command to invoke your editor, including the
    filename of the temporary file.

 #TEMPFILE <path&filename>

    This is the name of the temporary file to be used when writing the text
    during the use of MM_SuperCC.rexx.

 #GATEADDR <zone>:<net>/<node>[.<point>][@<domain>]

    Address of the gateway to be used for sending emails. If not specified it
    defaults to 2:2448/7808.999, which is my public InterNet-gateway.

 #GATENAME <name>

    Entry for the "To:"-field when sending emails to <GATEADDR>. Defaults to
    "AmiGate".

 #ECHOREC <name>

    Standard-receiver when sending echomails. Default: "All".

 #UNKNOWN <name>

    Default name for unlisted nodes. Defaults to "Unknown".

 #ZONE <number>

    Default zone when in wildcard-mode (network-file-support).

 #NET <number>

    Default net when in wildcard-mode (network-file-support).
@endnode
@prev "Installation"
@node "Usage" "MM_SuperCC.guide/Usage"
@next "Support"
Usage of MM_SuperCC
-------------------

 1.  Select the nodelist MM_SuperCC.rexx shall use for the wildcard-search.
     IMPORTANT: even if you do NOT use wildcard-search but mailing-lists you
                MUST select a nodelist in order to get the correct domain !

 2.  The program now should present you the correct domain. If it is correct
     just press <RETURN> twice, otherwise correct the domain and click on OK.

 3.  Select between wildcard-search, mailing-list or input-mode.

 3a. Wildcard-search:
     Enter the required wildcard. Only an asterix is valid ! Examples for
     correct wildcard-usage:

        2:*/0.0
        *:100/*.*
        2:2448/*.0
        *:*/0.0

     The following examples are INCORRECT:

        2:24*/*.0
        *:2448/78??.*

     IMPORTANT:
     On longer nodelists it may take a long, long time until the program
     finished scanning (even on an A4000/040) ! I suggest to create small
     part-nodelists of the regions you want to use or to create mailing-
     lists !

 3b. Mailing-lists:
     Just select the mailing-list which shall be used. Mailing-lists can
     either be created by hand or can be saved by MM_SuperCC.rexx (see step 
     5). See above for the format of mailing-lists.

 3c. Input-mode:
     A requester will appear, asking for your input in the following format:

     <address>[@<domain>] [<name>]
     or
     *<FQDA> [<realname>]
     or
     #<tagname> [<to-name>]

     Klick on OK when finished. Enter all addresses7tags this way. When no
     more address/tag is left, click on "Cancel".

     Examples for valid FTN-inputs:

     2:2448/7808
     2:2410/309.0
     2:2448/7022.0@fidonet
     2:2448/7808.999 AmiGate

     If [@<domain>] is ommited, default domain will be added. If [<name>]
     is omitted, the name will be looked up in the nodelist. If the address
     can not be found, name will default to the name specified in #UNKNOWN.

     Examples for valid email-inputs:

     *root@morphic.art-line.de
     *aminet@wuarchive.wustl.edu Urban Müller

     "Urban Müller" will be used in the CC:-header only. If it would be
     omitted, the complete RFC-address would be used for that.

     Examples for valid tagname-inputs:

     #AMIGA.GER
     #cCc.GeR
     #24000.ger Alle
     #flea.ger ---> ALL <---

     "Alle" will be used as the to-name in areatag 24000.GER, "---> ALL <---"
     as the to-name in areatag FLEA.GER. If the to-name is omitted, the
     default to-name (#ECHOREC) will be used.


 4.  A window containing all found nodes/tags will appear, including address
     and name of the sysop. You may delete an entry by selecting it an an
     click on OK. You then will be asked if you are sure to delete the entry.
     If the list is ok to send, just click on the OK-button without selecting
     an entry.

 5.  If you used wildcard-search or if you deleted a node during step 4 you
     will be asked if you want to save this list as a mailing-list. If so,
     just enter the name of the list an click on OK.

 6.  Next you have to select the file containing the text you want to send.
     You can either use your editor and type the text, or if you have the
     text already stored somewhere you may directly select this file and so
     not invoke your editor.

 7.  Enter a subject which will be used for the mails.

 8.  Enter the flow-type for the mails. Under normal circumstances you should
     select "normal" here.

 9.  If you select "Reflow text" any lines in the text with more than 80
     characters per line get wrapped.

 10. 'Return-Receipts': will send netmails with the "RRR"-flag, forcing the
     tosser of the receiver to send a message to you, when the message was
     received.

 11. 'Kill multiple receivers': often it may happen, that one person is
     listed more than once, but with different addresses. Therefore this
     person would get the message more often. If you select 'Yes' at this
     requester, each person will only get one copy of the message. The first
     address found will be used for mailing.

 12. If you force MM_SuperCC.rexx create a 'CC:-header' something like the
     following will appear at the top of the message:

        CC: Person A, Person B, Person XYZ, Bill Gates, Person Z, The Devil,
            Fields Of The Nephilim, Person 1, Person 2

     If not, the message will be sent as is.

     If you used wildcard-search and want CC:-headers you can MM_SuperCC force
     to show the search-pattern as the CC:-header instead of the names.

 13. Next you will have to select the matrix-area MM_SuperCC.rexx shall use.

 14. Last step: select if you want to do an immediate export of the mails or
     if they get exported somewhat later.
@endnode
